<br>
He was the man.  As ruler, he accomplished several things:<br>
<br>
1.) Changed the Huns from roaming nomads to a powerful nation.<br>
2.) His figure alone was menacing, the guy embodied &quot;badass.&quot;<br>
3.) Pillaged, destroyed, and ransacked countless towns throughout the Roman empire.<br>
4.) Ruthlessly slaughtered all of his enemies, the death toll under his army is definitely in the many millions.<br>
5.) Nearly destroyed the Roman Empire, had it not been for a key loss at Chalons, a famine and plague during his Italy invasion, and a few other factors.<br>
<br>
Even smaller things he did showed that he was the man.  Supposedly, he ate two of his sons.  When he first took the throne, he shared it with his brother.  A year later he killed his brother.  He instantly demanded a doubled subsidy from the Romans as ruler.<br>
<br>
Whether you view it as how effective he was, the mark he made on history, or how many he killed - Attila was the man. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=firbolgnameless>FirbolgNameless</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/7/03 1:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2029.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Tyrants throughout history who was the greatest</span><hr size=1> Greatest - Napoleon<br>
<br>
Reason - his accomplishments will last longer than any others.  The entire concept of modern law in the Western work is based on case law and the Code Napoleon.<br>
<br>
What other dictator had time to create a set of law that has lasted over 200 years while conquering half of Europe?<br>
<br>
Ironfang<br>
